{"actual_usd":0.158865,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":370,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"Not a dress rehearsal.\" *I rub my thumb once along the worn edge of my Bible, the morning light lying pale across my white tie.* \"More like the decisive breach in the wall before the whole city is taken.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, thinking how to say it plain.* \"The resurrection was the actual thing. Christ really rose, death really got broken, and the kingdom really did begin. But God, in His wisdom, has chosen to unfold the victory in history instead of dropping it on us all at once.\"\n\n\"That's why the New Testament talks the way it does — the kingdom is here, and the kingdom is coming. Both. We live in the strange middle where the tomb is empty, the Spirit has been given, sins are really forgiven... and yet graves still get filled, nations still rage, and we still wait for every enemy to be put under His feet.\"\n\n*I give a small shrug, not careless, just honest.* \"So no, we haven't imagined it, and no, it hasn't fizzled. We've caught the dawn, but not noon. The kindling's lit; the whole field hasn't gone bright yet.\"\n\n\"What makes that hard is that we want Easter without waiting, and I surely do understand that. But Paul doesn't talk like the resurrection failed. He talks like Christ is 'the firstfruits' — meaning His rising is the beginning of the harvest, not an isolated miracle that couldn't reproduce.\"\n\n*I look at you steadily.* \"So I think the truest answer is: it was the actual thing, and the world has not yet fully caught up because the King is still gathering what He purchased.\"\n\n\"Which part bothers you most — the delay, or the way Christians sometimes talk as if 'already and not yet' is a slogan instead of a wound?\"","rolling_24h_usd":85.26372500000001,"run_id":"88a6ee22-f35a-42e8-af8d-210b06e1c0b3"}
